video_transcription: Here are two stocks that could explode in the stock market this week. The first stock is Regetti Computing ticker symbol R G T I, and some people are calling this stock the next NVIDIA. Regetti Computing develops and operates quantum computers and provides cloud-based quantum computing services. Regetti Computing collaborates with companies such as Microsoft Azure, NVIDIA, and Riverlane to advance quantum computing technology and integrate it with classical computing systems. The stock is up nearly 1,000% this year, and analysts see it going much further due to their advantage in the quantum computing space. The next stock is Palantir Technologies ticker symbol P L T R, and this is an interesting one. Palantir Technologies provides data analytics and software solutions to help organizations integrate, manage, and analyze large data sets for decision-making and operational efficiency. They work with a range of clients, including government agencies such as the U.S. Department of Defense, as well as private sector companies like IBM, Airbus, and Morgan Stanley. The stock is currently up over 350% this year and is making new highs nearly every week. What are your thoughts on these stocks? Comment below.

video_transcription: There are three stocks I'll hold forever as a 36-year-old self-made millionaire and professional investor. Make sure to save this video. First is the SPDR S&P 500 ETF, which is an ETF that tracks the U.S. stock market and diversifies me between the 500 largest companies in the U.S. I'm happy to hold this ETF or any of these S&P 500 index funds forever because the S&P 500 has recovered from every crash in history, returns on average 10% per year, and is a long-term bet on the U.S. economy. Second on my list is Microsoft, as the company holds dominant positions in markets with long-term growth potential like cloud computing via Microsoft Azure and artificial intelligence via the company's 50% stake in chat GPT creator OpenAI. But the company also has cash cows like Windows Operating System, Microsoft Office, and their Xbox gaming division, all of which generate billions in revenue every year. Third on my list is Warren Buffett's Berkshire Hathaway, which I often call the Warren Buffett ETF since it's a collection of businesses ranging from technology stocks like Apple, credit card processors like American Express, and financial companies like Bank of America, all curated by Warren Buffett himself. There's a fourth investment I'd hold forever that you can read here in the caption, but make sure to follow if you want more practical investing videos.

video_transcription: Nike, does it have a rebound in 2025? It does. New CEO? I think the idea here that we have to keep in mind is none of us know Elliot Hill. That's this amazing part. New CEO of Nike. That's, I think, the point. No one on Wall Street or Main Street knows who Elliot Hill is, but everyone on campus does. Everyone on campus loves him. You have to be very attuned to letting all of your employees listen to all of your customers. That's not a one-person job. That's a team job. I think Nike is Nike. I think right now they need to do their reset, which they are going through. It's not going to be a very quick, seamless fix, but this is a business that has the largest marketing budget in the world. I totally agree that he's the right guy, and he's a Nike internal, like, through and through. It takes time. These turnarounds of big, Titanic ships takes time. That's what they are. These are giant. Yeah. I mean, it's like you have to, like, steer the ship, and it takes a while. You hope you don't hit the iceberg, right? I think stock-wise, there are better assets to play, and you can play that through Footlocker, which we like, or DKS, Dick's Sporting Goods, which we like, which are derivative plays on Nike without having to be in the Nike.

video_transcription: What is the biggest risk you see heading into 2025? Well, there's policy uncertainty. You know, will the tax policies, will sort of the protectionist policies have negative effects on stocks and on the economy? Might they have inflationary impact? The litmus test for that does come through the bond market. And so I think if you continue to see bond yields lifting, that could be a headwind for stocks.

The theory suggests there are a few different phases the market moves in, distribution, accumulation, markdown and markup. Distribution phases are phases where sellers are taking control of markets and markdown phases are the downward moves that happen after distributions. Accumulation is the opposite, it's where buys are accumulating and markup are the upward movements, the bullish movements that take place after accumulation. Now, if you go and look at a high timeframe or even a low timeframe for pretty much any asset that you trade, you'll notice that it moves in these phases of distribution, accumulation, markdown and markup. text: On January 1, 2025, the first major XRP transfer of the year occurred, with 500 million XRP (valued at $1.07 billion at a $2.13 XRP/USD rate) transferred between anonymous blockchain wallets, according to Whale Alert. #xrp #xrpcommunity #xrparmy #xrpripple #xrpnews #cryptoinvesting #cryptotrading #investingforbeginners #investment #cryptotok #ripple #cryptoforbeginners #shouldbeme
video_transcription: On January 1st, 2025, the first major XRP transfer of the year occurred. According to Well Alerts, 500 million XRP were transferred between anonymous blockchain wallets. The transfer, initiated by Ripple, aligns with their regular monthly escrow withdrawals, which typically releases 1 billion XRP in several transactions. However, this time, only one transaction with this magnitude was detected. Additionally, 30 million XRP was sent to a South Korean exchange, suggesting traders might be moving funds to cash and non-profits following XRP's recent rally from $0.60 to $3 in the past month. The event has sparked buzz within the XRP community, raising questions about its potential impact. What do you think is happening? Let us know in the comments. And Happy New Year, everyone!

text: Muita gente não sabe, mas poupar e investir não são a mesma coisa. Poupar é guardar dinheiro para emergências ou compras futuras, como uma forma de proteção. Já investir é fazer o seu dinheiro crescer, colocando ele para trabalhar por você e gerar mais renda ao longo do tempo. O dinheiro que fica parado na conta não se multiplica, mas o investido pode crescer de maneira exponencial com o tempo. Por isso, entender quando poupar e quando investir é essencial para uma vida financeira saudável. Quer aprender mais? Siga o @TRADINGFLOOR e descubra como fazer o seu dinheiro trabalhar para você! #PouparVsInvestir #EducaçãoFinanceira #DicasDeInvestimento #TradingFloor #CrescimentoFinanceiro

video_transcription: Poucas pessoas sabem, mas existe uma diferença fundamental entre poupar e investir. Quando você poupa, o seu foco é guardar dinheiro para situações de emergência ou para compras específicas no futuro, e como você se estivesse protegendo o seu dinheiro. Agora, quando você investe, você está fazendo o seu dinheiro trabalhar para você. O objetivo é que ele cresça e gere mais renda no longo prazo. Enquanto o dinheiro poupado fica parado na conta, o dinheiro investido pode se multiplicar ao longo do tempo. Por isso, é importante saber quando poupar e quando investir. Um não substitui o outro, mas ambos são essenciais para quem quer uma vida financeira saudável. Então, se você ainda acha que investir é complicado, siga o perfil Trading Floor para aprender mais sobre como fazer o seu dinheiro trabalhar para você. E claro, compartilhe esse vídeo com aquele amigo que ainda confunde poupar com investir.

text: Já deu pra perceber como investimento e patrimônio andam juntos, né? Enquanto investir é o caminho para fazer o seu dinheiro crescer, o patrimônio é o resultado de todas as suas escolhas financeiras. Ou seja, quanto melhor você investir, maior será o seu patrimônio no futuro. Quer aprender mais sobre como tomar as melhores decisões e fazer seu dinheiro trabalhar por você? Siga o @TRADINGFLOOR e comece a construir um patrimônio sólido hoje mesmo! #ConstruçãoDePatrimônio #InvestirComInteligência #EducaçãoFinanceira #TradingFloor

video_transcription: Você deve ser o último a saber sobre a verdadeira diferença entre investimento e patrimônio. Investimento é quando você aplica o seu dinheiro com o objetivo de gerar mais renda ou valor ao longo do tempo. É o que você faz quando você coloca o seu dinheiro em ações ou fundos, por exemplo, ou até em imóveis com o objetivo de obter o retorno. Já o patrimônio é o conjunto de todos os bens e recursos que você acumulou ao longo da sua vida. Isso inclui os seus investimentos, mas também o seu dinheiro que você tem guardado, a casa que você comprou, ou até mesmo o carro, entre outros bens que você tem. Então, enquanto o investimento é algo que você faz para aumentar o seu dinheiro, o patrimônio é o resultado de todas essas ações e decisões financeiras. Se você conhece alguém que ainda não entende essa diferença, compartilha esse vídeo com ele agora. E claro, não se esqueça de seguir o meu perfil e o perfil do Trading Floor para aprender mais sobre como construir patrimônio sólido e fazer os seus investimentos crescerem.

video_transcription: A lot of people want financial freedom in this life, but I feel like it's really important to understand that financial freedom does not just mean learning how to make more money. Financial freedom, in my opinion, means learning how to do money God's way so that money doesn't constantly stress you out for the rest of your life or take the throne of your heart for the rest of your life. So if you're looking to become financially free in all the ways, let's look into what God has to say about it. Matthew 6, 24, "'No one can serve two masters. "'Either you will hate the one and love the other "'or you will be devoted to the one and despise the other. "'You cannot serve both God and money.'" In addition to that, Matthew 6, verse 31, "'So do not worry about what you'll eat, "'about what you'll drink, about what you'll wear, "'but seek first the kingdom of God "'and all these things will be given to you as well.'" So what is God saying about financial freedom? Lesson number one, you cannot serve money over God. You should not prioritize money over prioritizing your relationship and your trust in God. Now you might be thinking, I don't serve money, I don't prioritize money over God. Okay, well, let's do a quick little heart check. If you are always worrying about your finances, if every decision you make is backed up by the fear or the thought in regards to your financial situation, you're serving money. It's one thing to be wise. It's a whole nother thing to be so overly obsessed that you don't even realize that subconsciously money has complete control over your life. So learn to flip it. Let God take control. Don't chase after money. Chase after God and his calling over your life. And as you do, watch how God begins to pave the way for financial freedom to take place in your life. All right, lesson two, let's dive in. Matthew 24, 14. "'It will be like a man going on a journey "'who called his servants and entrusted his wealth to them. "'To one he gave five bags of gold, "'to another, two bags, and to the other, one bag, "'each according to his ability.'" Pause. God said, each according to his ability. What does that mean? God will only bless you with the amount of money that he knows you are capable of handling. In other words, he trusts that you will manage that money well. How's your budgeting going? The Bible also says, do not be a slave to the lender. So how is it going with you working towards getting out of debt? Are you prioritizing that? The Bible talks about numerous times the importance of being generous with your money. Are you generous with your money? Do you have a giving heart with the money that you do have? And lastly, are you putting your money towards good investments, no matter how small or how big? Are you being wise with your investment choices? In summary, two of the servants put their money to work, and they ended up getting more money back. So much so that God, or this man in this story, praised his servants. He said, well done, you have been faithful with the few that I gave you. Therefore, I can trust you with the more that I want to give you. I will put you in charge of more. I will give you more. But the other servant, he hid that money. He saved it, most likely out of fear. And he thought that that was the wise choice to make. But his master, aka God, literally said, that was a lazy choice. You did not sow so that you could reap. You did not plant what I blessed you with so that you could harvest more of what I want to bless you with. Therefore, you have mismanaged your money, and I cannot trust you with more. God doesn't just give you money so that you can save, save, save for your own selfish ambitions. Is saving smart? Absolutely, but to an extent. If you are saving out of fear all the time, rather than figuring out and managing where to put that money towards wise investments that God is calling you to make, towards being generous, towards getting out of debt, things of that nature, then what are you doing? Do money God's way. Because when you do, when we do, true financial freedom, it's right there.

video_transcription: As much as I hate to see a game end like this, this is a moving screen. You can't just not call it because it makes the finish less entertaining. Right here, she's set for the screen. If she doesn't move, it's perfectly legal, there's no problem. But, she does move. A lot. Look at her base, look at how wide she is. She's lunging over to the side. She gives a little elbow at the end, too. The referee's gotta call that, no matter how unpopular it is. This was an excellent game, and a great showcase for women's basketball. Although neither Paige Beckers or Kaitlyn Clark played their best game, it was competitive throughout, and the Stars showed up down the stretch when their teams needed them. It looked like Iowa was gonna pull away before UConn mounted a comeback down the stretch to come within one point. Which is why it's so difficult that the game had to end like this. Like most fans, I wanted to see nothing more than for Paige and UConn to get one last shot up for a chance to win the game. But unfortunately, the rules are the rules no matter how much time is on the clock, and the referee made the right call in this situation.

video_transcription: awards are over, so here's who won all of the big categories. Best mobile game went to Bellatro, because of course it did. Best fighting game went to Tekken 8, and now that Clive from Final Fantasy 16 is in the game, I'm gonna start playing again. Best performance went to Mileena Juergens for Senua's Saga Hellblade 2, which is very well deserved. Best debut went to Bellatro, which you're going to be seeing a lot of. I personally did really want Animal World, but this is okay with me. Best adaptation did not go to Arcane, it went to Fallout, but still Ella Purnell was gonna win either way. Best narrative went to Metaphor Refantasio, which is great because it has a great story. Best art direction also went to Metaphor Refantasio, which I would give it that just for the UI alone. Best VR and AR game went to Batman Arkham Shadow. Best sim and strategy game went to Frostpunk 2. Best community support went to Baldur's Gate 3 for all of their massive updates they had this year. Best sports and racing game went to EA Sports FC 25. Best multiplayer, it didn't surprise me at all and I think it is very well deserved that Helldivers 2 took this one home. Best audio design went to Senua's Saga Hellblade 2. For the most anticipated game, of course it was going to go to GTA 6, but honestly I'm excited for literally all of these. The best action game went to Black Myth Wukong, which makes a ton of sense because that game is like pure action. Best score and music went to Final Fantasy 7 Rebirth, which I'll say it again, the music alone made me emotional. Like other categories, Metaphor Refantasio also won best RPG. Best independent game I wish went to Animal Well, but it went to Bellatro. I personally wanted to see Prince of Persia The Lost Crown win the best action or adventure game, but Astro Bot won and I'm okay with that. I thought Fortnite, with all of their massive updates they've brought to the game, especially this year, would give them the best ongoing game, but it went to Helldivers 2. Best game direction went to Astro Bot, which if you have to give them anything, you have to give them a ton of credit for shipping this game for a team of under 100 people. And finally, the game of the year did not go to Metaphor Refantasio, it didn't go to Black Myth Wukong, it didn't go to my personal favorite Final Fantasy 7 Rebirth, and it didn't go to the DLC or the card game, but any of these would be great picks. But it did go to Astro Bot and I will say, super well deserved. That is an incredible game and I want to play more of it and I'm going to literally right after this. At the end of the day, 2024 was an insane year for gaming and if Astro Bot wasn't your game of the year, that's okay. That shouldn't dictate how you feel about any of the games this year. You're totally valid and I'm just glad that we had such a great year and we're going to have an even better, probably, 2025.

video_transcription: six-figure career path that I wish I knew about when I was an undergrad. This is also a career path that's projected to grow, not shrink, over the next 10 to 20 years. It involves a lot of strategy, decision making, and working with a bunch of different teams. And pays well, you'll probably start out making between 70 to 90k right out of college, but within 5 to 10 years could definitely be making 150, 175, 200k. I'm specifically talking about a supply chain analyst role. This is someone who could be making decisions about the pros and cons of switching to an all-electric vehicle fleet. Or if you're in the food industry, you could be trying to figure out how to secure your supply of avocados. If you're interested in sustainability, this could be an awesome career path. And also great if you really like retail, because more and more orders are going to be placed online, and they need people to figure out the best way to get an order from a warehouse to the customer. video_transcription: One of my favorite techniques for building bigger shoulders is compound sets. A compound set is doing two exercises back to back for the same muscle group without rest. Start out with dumbbell lateral raises for 15-20 reps and immediately go into smith machine shoulder presses. Shoot for 8-10 reps here and aim for 4 total sets.

video_transcription: Number 4. Focus on compound movements. These are exercises that work multiple muscle groups at the same time, making them incredibly efficient for building muscle fast. Squats, deadlifts, and bench presses are great examples. Squats hit your legs, glutes, and core. Deadlifts engage your legs, back, and core. And bench presses work your chest, shoulders, and triceps. By sticking to these compound exercises, you'll stimulate more muscle fibers and see quicker results than if you're only doing isolation exercises like bicep curls or leg extensions. But don't worry, those can be added later to target specific muscles once the basics are mastered.

video_transcription: This is my kinds of dumb chart because you need to be more specific when you call yourself or somebody else dumb. The three aspects of being dumb are low intelligence, goofy personality, or bad decisions, and usually it's just a combination of a few. If you just have low intelligence, you're a nitwit. I'll throw in a little dumb personality in your p-brain, see how it works? A 50-50 combination is a doofus. If you're taken to the extreme, you're a dipstick. Mostly a dumb personality, but with the kinda low intelligence, you're a dolt. And if the only thing dumb about you is your personality, you're just a goof. If you have a dumb personality, but you also make some bad decisions, you're a goon. And if it's a combination of the two, you're an oaf. Same version of that is a blockhead. If you just make bad decisions with a little bit of a dumb personality, you're a moron. But if we're just talking bad decisions, that's a fool. Moving on to bad decisions, with a little bit of a low intelligence, you're a dunce. And if you think stupid and you act stupid, you're an idiot. If you need a stronger word than that, I'd go with nincompoop. Finally, if you have low intelligence with a little bit of bad decisions sprinkled in, that's an imbecile. video_transcription: Sometimes you just need a few ideas to get you through until your next paycheck, so here's how to make 4 dinners for 2 people for just $20. The first dinner I've already shared, which was the poor man's meal. All you need to make this is steak cut french fries, pepper stir fry, and some hot dogs, so this is a $3.75 dinner. I already have a full length video on this, but all I did was cut my steak cut french fries into 1 inch pieces, I rough chopped my pepper stir fry, and then I cut my hot dogs into 1 inch pieces as well. Everything gets sauteed together in a skillet, I did start with the pepper stir fry just to give it a head start since it was still frozen, and then I added in my bite sized potatoes and lastly my hot dogs, and once everything is golden brown, this is ready to serve. You can eat this as is, but I like to top mine with some ketchup. The second dinner I made was hot ham and cheese sandwiches with some tomato soup on the side. I took a block of cheddar cheese and cut it into bite sized pieces, I did the same with a package of smoked deli ham. I took 4 hamburger buns and topped them each with some of my ham and cheese mixture, covered this with aluminum foil, and then I baked this at 350 degrees for 20 minutes, and while it was baking, I went ahead and prepared my tomato soup per the canned instructions. The third dinner was smothered burritos with a side of Spanish rice, and this is loosely inspired by a Taco Bell dish called an enchirito. This meal I made all in the microwave, so I started off by grating a block of pepper jack cheese. Then I had two of these XXL beef and bean burritos, these were thawed, and I topped them each with some green enchilada sauce, and I microwaved these for a minute and a half per plate. I also microwaved a pouch of Spanish rice per the package instructions, and I split that between the two plates. I topped the entire plate with the shredded pepper jack cheese, and then I put it back in the microwave for 1 minute per plate. The final dinner was a very easy mock cottage pie. I mixed a pouch of instant potatoes with 2 cups of boiling water per the package instructions, in this case I'm using the loaded baked mashed potatoes, and I had a can of Campbell's condensed beef and vegetable soup. I mixed that with a can of drained carrots and a can of drained peas, I topped it with my potato mixture, spread it out over the top, and then I baked this at 400 degrees for 20 minutes. Some of the gravy from the soup had bubbled up over the top, which I brushed all over the potatoes to give it a really nice uniform look. All four of these dinners were very filling and delicious, and I hope it provides a source of inspiration for anyone who needs it. I've also included screenshots with the items you need to buy and the basic preparation instructions for each of these four dinners for you to screenshot and keep on your phone for reference.

video_transcription: All right, so I've kicked off this exciting and challenging project, upgrading and customizing a 1962 Ford Country sedan. The goal here is simple, turn this classic into something that not only packs some serious power under the hood, but still holds on to its vintage charm. I'm talking air suspension, a lowered frame, a brand-new floor, and a bunch of custom touches to give it that standout, one-of-a-kind look. First up, we tackled the front suspension. Our motto for this phase, keep it fun and budget-friendly. The idea was to improve not just the overall performance, but also make the ride way smoother and more comfortable. Next, we moved on to adding an air suspension setup. To be real, finding the right kit off the shelf wasn't happening, so we decided to go DIY. The plan is to go with a two-link rear setup paired with a Panhard bar. Now, we're not entirely sure how this design is going to perform. So if you have any feedback, good or bad, we'd love to hear it. Seriously, every bit of input helps. And then we bring that front leg out to the side and we're doing a similar movement, but now we're hitting the adductor group, which is the inner thighs. video_transcription: What is your English level? Beginner, Intermediate or Advanced? Get ready, because I am going to test your English level. My name is Mati from POC English and in this lesson we are going to have an English level test to understand your level of English. Before we start, let me explain what we are going to do. There are 30 questions divided in 3 different levels. Beginner, Intermediate and Advanced. I will show you the question, then you will have 5 seconds to come up with the answer. Remember, if you need more time, you can pause the video, think about the question and your answer and play it again. That's ok. Don't forget to keep count of the number of correct answers you have, because we are going to need it. In addition, I will explain the grammar and vocabulary behind each question, so that you know why your answer was wrong, if it was wrong. So, it's not just a test, but we are going to learn a lot of things together. Now, let's get into it. Let's start the test and we will start with the beginner level. Are you ready? The first 10 questions are for the beginner level. The first 5 questions are for A1 level. Let's start. Which sentence is correct? He live on London, He live in London or He lives in London. He lives in London. But why? Because this is present simple. In present simple, we have subject plus verb. When the subject is 3rd person singular, which is he, she or it, the verb takes an S. So, I live, you live, he lives. In addition, we never say on London, we say in London. In plus city, not on. Question 2. Which sentence is correct? I don't like coffee. I doesn't like coffee. I does like coffee. The answer is I don't like coffee. But why? Again, this is simple present but negative. To make a simple present sentence negative, we use don't for I, you, we and they and doesn't for he, she and it. So, I don't, you don't, he doesn't, she doesn't, it doesn't, you don't, they don't and we don't. Question 3. Which sentence is correct? He goes to work in bus. He goes to work by bus. He goes to work by the bus. He goes to work by bus. But why? When we are talking about the means of transport, bus, car, taxi, we use by. By bus, by train, by taxi, by plane. Another important point. We never use the article the before means of transport. So, we never say I went by the bus, by the train, by the plane. Unless we know which plane or which train or which means of transport we are talking about. But in general, we don't. Next question. Which one is correct? George has very big car. George a very big car has. George has a very big car. George has a very big car. But why? In present simple, we should use this structure. Subject plus verb plus the rest of the sentence. So, the correct answer would be George has. So, B is not correct. But what about A and C? In English, for singular nouns, we need to use an article. A, an, or the. In this case, our noun is car. So, we must say a car, not just car. Therefore, C is correct. Let's get to the next question. Which one is correct? Look at this house over there. Look at that house over here. Look at that house over there. Look at that house over there. But why? In English, for something which is close to us, we use this. For example, this microphone, this laptop, this mouse, this book, because it's close to me. But for something which is far away from you, we use that. For example, that camera, that building, that mirror. And there are two words. Here, which is around you, close to you. And there, which is far from you. There, here. This, that. So, I should say, this here, that there. Look at that house over there.

video_transcription: Top six downsides of trusts. Number one, initial cost. Cheap advice is cheap. It's best to budget about the same as one month of care fees. Number two, complexity. Learning a new way of thinking can be a challenge. Some people struggle with the concept of not owning a thing, but controlling it. Number three, loss of sole control. When your assets are in a trust, the settler no longer has sole control of them. The trustees, the partners and adult kids, have the control and manage them for the beneficiaries, the partners, and then the adult children. Number four, trust taxes. Yes, trusts can pay tax. Normal trusts have complex tax calculations. Setting up a family home protection plus trust reduces all the tax complexity. Number five, trustee disputes. Where the family are trustees, make sure everybody gets along, otherwise the settler may have to remove one of the trustees. And number six, most importantly, public perception. Most people think trusts are super complicated or for the super rich, and they're not. We do them for mom and dad to protect their home from care fees and taxes every single day. video_transcription: While Aaron is buzzing my hair, we thought we would do a quick compilation video of all of the negatives that we have experienced about Costa Rica. The number one that most people complain about is that nothing gets done quickly here. The people do not just live to work and so it's a different mindset. So if they tell you a construction job is going to get done in two weeks, it's probably going to be four. Consideration number two is that anything that has to be shipped in is very expensive. So something like olive oil is going to be double the price that it would be in the United States or Canada. Another downside is that most of the things that they do get shipped in here are shipped from China and are very poor quality. We had our daughter bring us our chef's knives and a good pan because the pans and knives are terrible. The linens and towels and things like that, everybody says it's terrible quality. We also live in a beach town, so there's literally just sand everywhere. You can't get rid of it. And also because we live in a beach town, goods and services are just more expensive than they would be on the interior. We don't care about this one, but if you love AC, none of the restaurants have AC. Almost all of them are open air restaurants or you sit outside. So you have got to love warmth. Again, not a difficulty for us, but the sun goes down every day by 536-ish. So we adjusted and get up super early. But if that's an issue for you, if you get up late, you're not going to have but just a few hours of daylight time. And the fact that the sun rises between 530 and 6-ish, so it's already starting to heat up by 9 o'clock. Another thing is because Costa Rica is the size of West Virginia. The whole country is the size of West Virginia. So literally every square mile, either people live there or it's a city. So the maximum speed limit that we have ever seen here was 60 kilometers per hour, which is what, Erin? About 45? No, it's like 35. No, we saw an 80 kilometer an hour at once. Oh, that's true. Which is like 50-ish, 52, 53, and that was like on a highway. So everything's slow going. Even that was interspersed with little towns and you had to drop to like 40 kilometers an hour. Yeah, so it is slow going anywhere you drive.

video_transcription: the UK and living in London has been amazing. I posted a list of things that I love about living in London so now let's go through things that I don't love. I know I'm not gonna say the weather but I am gonna say rain because the way that the rain hits this country is just different. Now the next thing is how cold people can be and I think it's just part of a big city life people kind of zoning out but especially on the tube I've spoken about this so many times people don't look up or if they look up they completely ignore what they see. Elderly, pregnant women, women with kids. I find it quite heartbreaking to see. I try to smile at people and sometimes people either smile back and you can see they're kind of taken back or sometimes they look at me like I'm a complete weirdo. Now I cannot stand the fact that the tube has like no air. I've never been on a subway or a metro or train where you can't open the sides of the windows on only the back. There have been so many times where I've seen people nearly faint and there's nothing that you can do because there's literally no air. Now next one is a lack of really really fresh fruit and veg anywhere else when you go to a market there are so many people that come that actually grow these vegetables and stuff and they you can literally smell the tomato when you lift it up to your face whereas in London I've not been able to find that like I get everything at Tesco and I'm happy with it but sometimes you just want like a really good peach or really good strawberries or really good tomato and I've just not been to any market that sells that. The amount of money that goes out of my bank account every single month for just taking the underground is insane and then train drivers also get underpaid and there's strikes all the time which is just so unfair makes no sense and yeah taking a train to Manchester on like a weekend will cost you the same as taking a flight somewhere in Europe. Now this is going to be a controversial one and it's going to be the drinking culture. I think the drinking culture in the UK is like nowhere else I've been and again nothing against drinking but I think it's really excessive like really really really excessive it's such a big part of a culture but also I moved from Bali where people are very very health conscious and like a lot of people don't drink or people don't really do that and no one goes for like after work drinks because again everyone can make their own choices but it's definitely like per culture like I think in Germany probably would be like people drink a lot of beer as well. Now the next thing is heating. I feel like the heating in the UK is so weird it's either too hot or too cold and the tube is like super super hot and then the offices are either like cold or way too warm like I think the UK has a difficult time adjusting their temperatures. text: Is the water in your home breaking you out? #thatboweglow #acne #healthyskin #breakouts #breakoutskin
video_transcription: the water in your home be breaking you out? The answer is turning out to be yes. So both the water that you drink and the water that you bathe with or even wash your face with, it can actually impact the microbiome. Ingredients in the water and concentrations of those ingredients, including things like chlorine, can affect the microbiome in your gut and on your skin and can actually lead to things like breakouts. So if you've ever moved from one location to another, your skin starts acting up. It might be the water.

video_transcription: Nếu như bạn còn đang nhầm lẫn giữa đẩy mụn purging và bị mụn breakout Hôm nay cùng tớ phân biệt 2 vấn đề da này nhá Thứ nhất, purging, đẩy mụn, đây hiện tượng thường xuất hiện khi chúng mình sử dụng BHA hoặc là Red Noise Thời gian đẩy mụn tối đa là 4-6 tuần Nếu như mà quá các quãng thời gian này mà da của chúng ta vẫn liên tiếp mọc mụn thì xin chê buồn cậu đã bị breakout Thứ hai, breakout là hiện tượng mà da bị nổi mụn hoặc là bùng phát mụn ở những khu vực da mà trước đó chưa từng có mụn Khi đã phân biệt đẩy mụn và bị mụn thì chúng mình sẽ cùng hướng tới biện pháp xử lý phù hợp nhá Đầu tiên với purging thì cứ tiếp tục sử dụng BHA hoặc là Red Nose Đồng thời bổ sung thêm và routine các sản phẩm chấm mụn để nhanh làm khô khối mụn Và thâm do purging để lại thì cũng sẽ nhanh mở hơn khi mà chúng mình sử dụng các sản phẩm chữa niacinamide hoặc là vitamin C Còn nếu như không may mắn bị breakout thì hãy giản tần suất sử dụng hoặc là ngưng dùng BHA và Red Nose Bổ sung thêm các thành phần làm dịu da như rau má và vitamin B5 Trong trường hợp mà breakout quá là nặng gây stress thì hãy đi thăm khám bác sĩ để có được một pháp đồ điều trị hợp lý nha Bye!

Breakouts are typically consistent, involve all types of pimples, last a long time, and can be painful or itchy. While purging, on the other hand, is usually caused from ingredients like retinols, AHAs, and BHAs, and typically clears in less than four weeks, and isn't itchy or painful. You need to try sesanic acid acne treatment to help. It reduces blemish size and oil levels, unblocks pores, and is gentle on the skin, and affordable too.

video_transcription: Want an easy way to make money in Forex? Master my favorite trading setup in five simple steps. Step 1. Mark the liquidity level on both sides of the market. Buy side liquidity and sell side liquidity before 3 p.m. GMT plus 8. Step 2. Mark out the London kill zone that happens from 3 to 4 p.m. Step 3. Wait for the liquidity to sweep the liquidity levels on either side during the kill zone. Buy side or sell side, either one is fine. Step 4. Wait for rejection of the liquidity level and a fair value gap to form. Step 5. Wait for price to tap the new fair value gap and enter with a strict 1 is to 2 risk to reward ratio with stop loss covering the swept liquidity area. So here is an example of how it works in the charts. Here on the GBPUSD 15-minute chart, we can identify the high and low levels created before the London kill zones. This will be your buy side liquidity and sell side liquidity waiting to be swept. Once the bottom side is swept, we wait for a bullish fair value gap to form before setting a buy limit with stops covering the low, targeting A1 is to 2 risk to reward ratio. And after a while, as you can see, we have smashed our TP. Now you know my favorite trading setup. Save the video and practice it on TradingView. If you want more, check out our TikToks and click on the Instagram icon for free signals and education.
